# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gdscript-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] The name *bytecode* stems from instruction sets that have one-byte opcodes followed by optional parameters.
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] Intermediate representations such as bytecode may be output by programming language implementations to ease interpretation, or it may be used to reduce hardware and operating system dependence by allowing the same code to run cross-platform, on different devices.
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] Bytecode may often be either directly executed on a virtual machine (a p-code machine, i.e., interpreter), or it may be further compiled into machine code for better performance.
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] Since bytecode instructions are processed by software, they may be arbitrarily complex, but are nonetheless often akin to traditional hardware instructions: virtual stack machines are the most common, but virtual register machines have been built also.
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] Different parts may often be stored in separate files, similar to object modules, but dynamically loaded during execution.
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] A bytecode program may be executed by parsing and *directly* executing the instructions, one at a time.
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] This kind of *bytecode interpreter* is very portable.
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] Some systems, called dynamic translators, or *just-in-time* (JIT) compilers, translate bytecode into machine code as necessary at runtime.
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] This makes the virtual machine hardware-specific but does not lose the portability of the bytecode.
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] For example, Java and Smalltalk code is typically stored in bytecode format, which is typically then JIT compiled to translate the bytecode to machine code before execution.
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] This introduces a delay before a program is run, when the bytecode is compiled to native machine code, but improves execution speed considerably compared to interpreting source code directly, normally by around an order of magnitude (10x).
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] Because of its performance advantage, today many language implementations execute a program in two phases, first compiling the source code into bytecode, and then passing the bytecode to the virtual machine.
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] There are bytecode based virtual machines of this sort for Java, Raku, Python, PHP, Tcl, mawk and Forth (however, Forth is seldom compiled via bytecodes in this way, and its virtual machine is more generic instead).
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] The implementation of Perl and Ruby 1.8 instead work by walking an abstract syntax tree representation derived from the source code.
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] More recently, the authors of V8 and Dart have challenged the notion that intermediate bytecode is needed for fast and efficient VM implementation.
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] Both of these language implementations currently do direct JIT compiling from source code to machine code with no bytecode intermediary.
[src:gdscript-deep/bytecode] Compiled code can be analysed and investigated using a built-in tool for debugging the low-level bytecode.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] In computer programming, **duck typing** is an application of the duck test—"If it walks like a duck and it quacks like a duck, then it must be a duck"—to determine whether an object can be used for a particular purpose.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] With nominative typing, an object is of a given type if it is declared as such (or if a type's association with the object is inferred through mechanisms such as object inheritance).
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] With duck typing, an object is of a given type if it has all methods and properties required by that type.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] Duck typing may be viewed as a usage-based structural equivalence between a given object and the requirements of a type.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] In some statically typed languages such as Boo and D, class type checking can be specified to occur at runtime rather than at compile time.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] C# can invoke dynamic typing which behaves similar to duck typing, through the keyword `dynamic`.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] Duck typing is similar to, but distinct from, structural typing.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] Structural typing is a static typing system that determines type compatibility and equivalence by a type's structure, whereas duck typing is dynamic and determines type compatibility by only that part of a type's structure that is accessed during runtime.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] The TypeScript, Elm and Python languages support structural typing to varying degrees.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] Protocols and interfaces provide a way to explicitly declare that some methods, operators or behaviors must be defined.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] If a third-party library implements a class that cannot be modified, a client cannot use an instance of it with an interface unknown to that library even if the class satisfies the interface requirements.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] A common solution to this problem is the adapter pattern.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] In contrast, with duck typing, the object would be accepted directly without the need for an adapter.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] Template (also called generic) functions or methods apply the duck test in a static typing context; this brings all of the advantages and disadvantages of static versus dynamic type checking.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] Duck typing can also be more flexible in that only the methods actually called at runtime must be implemented, while templates require implementations of all methods that cannot be proven unreachable at compile time.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] In languages such as Java, Scala and Objective-C, reflection may be employed to inspect whether objects implement methods or add necessary methods at runtime.
[src:gdscript-deep/duck-typing] For example, Java's MethodHandle API can be used in this manner.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] A **game engine** is a software framework primarily designed for video game development, which may include specialized software libraries and packages, such as level editors.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] The term "engine" is a direct analogue of "software engine", having it employed across sectors of the software industry.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Furthermore, *game engine* may also refer to the integrated development environment as an interface behind the given framework, typically a suite of visual development tools and features for developing video games.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Game developers can use game engines to create and publish video games across platforms, such as desktops, mobile devices, video game consoles, and other types of computers.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] The core functionalities commonly covered by a game engine are a 2D or 3D renderer, physics engine, audio engine, scripting, animation, artificial intelligence, networking, streaming, memory management, threads, localization support, scene graph, and cinematics.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Game engine developers often economize game development through reuse or adaptation of abstractions built into game engines for production of various games, or through porting of videogames from a single to other target platforms.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] In many cases, game engines provide a suite of visual development tools in addition to reusable software components.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] These tools are generally provided in an integrated development environment to enable simplified, rapid development of games in a data-driven manner.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Game-engine developers often attempt to preempt implementer needs by developing robust software suites, which include many elements a game developer may need to build a game.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Most game-engine suites provide facilities that ease development, such as graphics, sound, physics and artificial intelligence (AI) functions.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Like other types of middleware, game engines usually provide platform abstraction, allowing the same game to run on various platforms (including game consoles and personal computers) with few, if any, changes made to the game source code.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Often, programmers design game engines with a component-based architecture that allows specific systems in the engine to be replaced or extended with more specialized (and often more expensive) game-middleware components.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Some game engines comprise a series of loosely-connected game middleware components that can be selectively combined to create a custom engine, instead of the more common approach of extending or customizing a flexible integrated product.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] However achieved, extensibility remains a high priority for game engines due to the wide variety of uses for which they are applied.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Despite the specificity of the name "game engine", end users often re-purpose game engines for other kinds of interactive applications with real-time graphical requirements—such as marketing demos, architectural visualizations, training simulations, and modeling environments.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Some game engines only provide real-time 3D rendering capabilities instead of the wide range of functionality needed by games.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] These engines rely upon the game developer to implement the rest of this functionality or to assemble it from other game-middleware components.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] These types of engines are generally referred to as a "graphics engine", "rendering engine", or "3D engine" instead of the all-encompassing term "game engine".
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] This terminology is inconsistently used, as many full-featured 3D game engines are simply referred to as "3D engines".
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Examples of graphics engines include: Crystal Space, Genesis3D, Irrlicht, OGRE, RealmForge, Truevision3D, and Vision Engine.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Modern game- or graphics-engines generally provide a scene graph—an object-oriented representation of the 3D game-world which often simplifies game design and can be used for more efficient rendering of vast virtual worlds.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Most game engines or graphics engines use a Graphics API, which eases communication with the GPU.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] But older games did not have hardware acceleration or GPUs and had to build their own software renderer.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] As technology ages, the components of an engine may become obsolete or insufficient for the requirements of a given project.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Since the complexity of programming an entirely new engine may result in unwanted delays (or necessitate that a project restart from the beginning), an engine-development team may elect to update their existing engine with newer functionality or components.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Game engines are not limited to use in the video game field, and have found uses in other scientific fields.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Part of this is due to game engines being optimized for consumer-grade computing equipment rather than high-performance computing, allowing researchers to develop programs for their use on lower cost machines.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Game engines also simplify many of the computing operations needed for scientific software, including graphics, networking, and interactivity, reducing the need to develop these features themselves.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Before game engines, games were typically written as singular entities: a game for the Atari 2600, for example, had to be designed from the bottom up to make optimal use of the display hardware—this core display routine is now called the kernel by developers of games for older systems.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Other platforms had more leeway, but even when display was not a concern, memory constraints usually sabotaged attempts to create the data-heavy design that an engine needs.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Even on more accommodating platforms, very little could be reused between games.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] The rapid advance of arcade hardware—which was the leading edge of the market at the time—meant that most of the code would have to be thrown out afterwards anyway, as later generations of games would use completely different game designs that took advantage of extra resources.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Thus, most game designs through the 1980s were designed through a hard-coded rule set with a small number of levels and graphics data.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Since the golden age of arcade video games, it became common for video game companies to develop in-house game engines for use with first-party software.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] A notable example of an in-house game engine on home consoles in the mid-1980s was the smooth side-scrolling engine developed by Shigeru Miyamoto's team at Nintendo for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES).
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] The engine they had developed for the side-scrolling racing game *Excitebike* (1984) was later employed for the scrolling platformer *Super Mario Bros.* (1985).
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] This allowed Mario to smoothly accelerate from a walk to a run, rather than move at a constant speed like in earlier platformers.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] While third-party game engines were not common until the rise of 3D computer graphics in the 1990s, several 2D game creation systems were produced in the 1980s for independent video game development.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Klik & Play (1994) is another legacy offering that is still available.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] The term *game engine* emerged in the mid-1990s, particularly with the rise of 3D games like first-person shooters, which often featured a dedicated first-person shooter engine.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] For instance, Epic Games, founded by Tim Sweeney, debuted its Unreal Engine in 1998.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Later games, such as id Software's *Quake III Arena* and Epic Games' *Unreal* (1998), were designed with this approach in mind, with the engine and content developed separately.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] At the very least, reusable engines make developing game sequels faster and easier, which is a valuable advantage in the competitive video game industry.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] While a strong rivalry existed between Epic Games and id Software around 2000, Epic Game's Unreal Engine has since become far more popular than id Tech 4 and its successor, id Tech 5.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Modern game engines are some of the most complex applications written, often featuring dozens of finely-tuned systems interacting to ensure a precisely-controlled user experience.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] The continued evolution of game engines has created a strong separation between rendering, scripting, artwork, and level design.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] As such, it is now common, for example, for a typical game development team to have several times as many artists as actual programmers.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] While third-party game engines are predominantly used in the development of first-person shooter games, they are also being used across other genres.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] For example, Gamebryo is used in *The Elder Scrolls III: Morrowind* and *Dark Age of Camelot*, whereas Unreal Engine 2 is used in *Lineage II*.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Game engines are also used for games originally developed for home consoles, with RenderWare for the *Grand Theft Auto* and *Burnout* franchises as an example.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Due to modern multi-core systems and growing demands in realism, exploiting threads has become more important.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Separate threads of execution within a game engine manage intensive operations, including rendering, asset streaming, audio playback, and physics simulation.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Racing games have typically been at the forefront of threading with the physics engine running in a separate thread long before other core subsystems were moved, partly because rendering and related tasks need updating at only 30–60 Hz.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] For example, on PlayStation 3, physics ran in *Need For Speed* at 100 Hz, versus *Forza Motorsport 2* at 360 Hz.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Although the term was first used in the 1990s, few earlier systems in 1980s are considered as game engines, such as Sierra's Adventure Game Interpreter (AGI) and SCI systems, LucasArts' SCUMM system and Incentive Software's Freescape engine (in 1986).
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Unlike most modern game engines, these game engines were never used in any third-party products (except for the SCUMM system, which was licensed to and used by Humongous Entertainment).
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] As game engine technology matures and becomes more user friendly, the application of game engines has widened in scope.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] They are now used for serious games: visualization, training, medical, and military simulation applications, with the CryEngine being one example.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] To improve accessibility, new hardware platforms are also now targeted by game engines, including mobile phones (e.g.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Additionally, more game engines are being built upon higher-level languages, such as Java, C# and .NET (e.g., TorqueX, and Visual3D.NET), Python (Panda3D), or Lua Script (Leadwerks).
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] As most 3D-rich games are now mostly limited by the power of a graphics card, the potential slowdown due to translation overheads of higher-level languages becomes negligible, while productivity gains offered by these languages serve the game engine developers' benefit.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] These recent trends are being propelled by companies such as Microsoft to support indie game development.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Microsoft developed XNA as the primary Software Development Kit (SDK) for all video games released on Xbox and their related products.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] This includes the Xbox Live Indie Games channel designed specifically for smaller developers who do not have the extensive resources necessary to box games for sale on retail shelves.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] It is becoming easier and cheaper than ever to develop game engines for platforms that support managed frameworks.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Producers of game engines decide how they allow users to use their products.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Just as gaming is an industry, so are the engines they are built off.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] The major game engines come at varying prices, whether it be in the form of subscription fees or license payments.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Unity and Unreal Engine are currently the two most popular choices for game developers.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Although the differences among the different game engines blur as they build their own tools on top of them, different game developers may be too used to a system to change, or attracted by the huge benefits of such engines regardless of pay-walls.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Free and open-source engines such as Godot, have seen a rise in popularity, particularly following the 2023 Unity pricing controversy which drove game developers and studios to seek engines with a permissive license.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Applied more broadly, game engines themselves can be described as middleware.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] In video games, however, *middleware* is often used to refer to subsystems of functionality within a game engine.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Some game middleware does only one thing, yet does it more convincingly or more efficiently than general purpose middleware.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] The four most-widely used middleware packages that provide subsystems of functionality include RAD Game Tools' Bink, Firelight FMOD, Havok, and Scaleform GFx.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] RAD Game Tools develops Bink for basic video rendering, along with Miles audio, and Granny 3D rendering.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Firelight FMOD is a low cost robust audio library and toolset.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Havok provides a robust physics simulation system, along with a suite of animation and behavior applications.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Scaleform provides GFx for high performance Flash UI and high-quality video playback, and an Input Method Editor (IME) addon for in-game Asian chat support.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Other middleware is used for performance optimization—for example Simplygon helps to optimize and generate level of detail meshes, and Umbra adds occlusion culling optimizations to 3D graphics.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Some middleware contains full source code, or is provided an API reference for a compiled binary library.
[src:gdscript-deep/game-engine] Some middleware programs can be licensed either way, usually for a higher fee for full source code.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot allows video game developers to create both 3D and 2D games using multiple programming languages, such as C++, C#, Python and GDScript.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] It makes use of a hierarchy of nodes to facilitate the development experience.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Classes can be derived from a node type to create more specialized node types that inherit behavior.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Nodes are organized inside of "scenes", which are reusable, instantiable, inheritable, and nestable groups of nodes.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Nodes are connected by signals, which can transmit data objects.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] All game resources, including scripts and graphical assets, are saved as part of the computer's file system (rather than in a database).
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] This storage solution is intended to facilitate collaboration between game development teams using software version control systems.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The engine enables developers to create both 2D and 3D games across desktop, mobile, browser, and console platforms without licensing fees.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The engine has received updates such as a path-tracing renderer for 3D graphics, improving its capabilities for realistic rendering.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] It has visual scripting, cross-platform deployment, and virtual reality integration.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The engine supports deployment to multiple platforms and allows specification of texture compression and resolution settings for each platform.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The website provides binaries only for the editor platforms, and exporting projects to other platforms is done within the Godot editor.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The Godot engine can be run on consoles, although popular consoles are not officially supported since it is not compatible with the engine's open-source license.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Games can be ported to consoles through third-party companies, including W4 Games, a commercial company founded by Godot coders.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] For CPU architectures, Godot officially supports x86 on all desktop platforms (both 32-bit and 64-bit where available) and has official ARM support on macOS, Linux, mobile platforms, and standalone Meta platforms (both 32-bit and 64-bit where available).
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot also supports a mobile XR port for Meta Quest devices running Horizon OS, allowing developers to create immersive applications directly on the headset without the use of a traditional computer.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot supports a variety of programming languages for making games, including the integrated language GDScript, C++ and C#.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Additionally, the engine includes GDNative (GDExtension as of Godot 4.x), a facility for creating bindings with other languages.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Officially-supported GDNative/GDExtension languages include C and C++.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Community-supported languages include Rust, Nim, Swift, and JavaScript.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Visual coding was originally supported by the built-in language VisualScript, designed to be a visual equivalent to GDScript.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] VisualScript was removed from the core engine in Godot 4.0.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot games running in the browser can interface with the browser's JavaScript code.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The Godot editor includes a text editor with auto indentation, syntax highlighting and code completion and folding.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] It also features a debugger with the ability to set breakpoints and program stepping.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot has its own built-in scripting language, GDScript, a high-level, gradually typed programming language which is syntactically similar to Python.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Unlike Python, GDScript is optimized for Godot's scene-based architecture and can specify strict typing of variables.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot's developers have stated that many alternative third-party scripting languages such as Lua, Python, and Squirrel were tested before deciding that using a custom language allowed for superior optimization and editor integration.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] GDScript is a continuously evolving scripting language, and changes and additions to it have been implemented for each major new release of Godot.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Typed arrays and typed dictionaries were added in 4.0 and 4.4 respectively.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The optional static types allow the C++ back end to apply optimizations that result in notably increased performance; statically typed GDScript has been observed to run more than 40% faster in release builds.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot 3.x's graphics engine uses either OpenGL ES or Vulkan is supported in newer versions; Metal support also exists on Apple platforms.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The engine supports normal mapping, specularity, dynamic shadows using shadow maps, baked and dynamic global illumination, and full-screen post-processing effects like bloom, depth of field, high-dynamic-range rendering, and gamma correction.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] A simplified shader language, similar to GLSL, is also incorporated.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Shaders can be used for materials and post-processing.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Alternatively, they can be created by manipulating nodes in a visual editor.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot also includes a separate 2D graphics engine that can operate independently of the 3D engine, but both can also work at the same time on the same display, so as to make complex mixes between 2D and 3D.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The 2D engine supports features such as lights, shadows, shaders, tile sets, parallax scrolling, polygons, animations, physics, and particles.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] It is also possible to mix 2D and 3D using a "viewport node".
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] To support the UI and 2D Vector graphics assets support, Godot has integrated a 3rd party library, ThorVG.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot contains an animation system with a GUI for skeletal animation, blending, animation trees, morphing, and real-time cutscenes.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot has its own in-house physics engine, and as of Godot 4.x allows third parties to integrate their own physics via GDExtension.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] In Godot 3.x, the Bullet physics engine is included and used by default.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] With Godot 4.4, the Jolt Physics engine was added, though not used as the default engine until the release of Godot 4.6.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The engine has been used in educational settings and by independent developers due to its free licensing and cross-platform support.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Juan 'reduz' Linietsky and Ariel 'punto' Manzur co-founded Codenix in 1999, a game development consulting company.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] As early as 2001, they began work on an engine then code-named "Larvotor" which was licensed to third-party companies in Argentina.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Over the course of the following ten years, the engine was renamed to "Legacy", "NG3D", "Larvita" and finally to "Godot".
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The name "Godot" was chosen in reference to Samuel Beckett's play *Waiting for Godot*, as it represents the never-ending wish of adding new features in the engine, which would get it closer to an exhaustive product, even though it never would.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Linietsky and Manzur joined OKAM and the company worked with a number of studios in the closed-source era including Square Enix.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Linietsky indicated that their work was hampered by political and economic instability in Argentina at the time however.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] By 2014 Linietsky was planning on moving away from Argentina, and he released the source code for Godot to the public on GitHub under the MIT License.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot joined the Software Freedom Conservancy (SFC) on 4 November 2015.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] On 22 June 2016, Godot received a $20,000 Mozilla Open Source Support (MOSS) "Mission Partners" award to be used to add WebSockets, WebAssembly and WebGL 2.0 support.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The 3.0 update for Godot involved addressing a long list of desired features requiring a major refactor of the engine that had been commercially impossible while in the closed-source era.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] With Miguel de Icaza's support, Godot received a $24,000 donation from Microsoft in 2017 to implement C# as a scripting language in Godot.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] A Patreon was launched, which enabled Linietsky and Verschelde to work on the project full time.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The 3.1 update added an OpenGL ES 2.0 renderer aimed at mobile hardware, as mobile support for ES 3.0 by manufacturers was then limited.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] In 2019 two teams were formed, with Linietsky's team focusing on the Vulkan branch (later released as 4.0) and Verschelde's team covering further updates to the 3.x branch.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Linietsky indicated that part of the issue was that the 3.x branch was built with older architectural principles in mind, such as single-core processors.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Thus, the intention was to redevelop the core architecture for 4.0 and account for modern principles.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] In 2020, Godot received a $250,000 Epic Games award to improve graphics rendering and the engine's built-in game development language, GDScript.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The 4.0 branch released in alpha form in early 2022, and was polished over the course of the year.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] That August, Linietsky and several other members of the Godot team established W4 Games to offer commercial services based on the engine, including console ports that cannot be included in its open-source codebase.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] In November, Godot announced plans to transition from the SFC to its own newly-formed Godot Foundation.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The full release of the 4.0 update with Vulkan support occurred in 2023, as well as the arrival of the Godot engine on the Epic Games Store.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The version on Epic is identical to others in terms of both content and licensing, with the storefront simply used as a means of distribution and for updating.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] However, the .NET/C# support version of the engine is not available on Epic Games Store, nor Itch and Steam as well.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] In September, Unity Technologies announced major changes to licensing for the Unity engine including the addition of "runtime fees" that would charge users on installation of Unity games.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] As a result, some developers switched from Unity to Godot, and Re-Logic donated $100,000 to Godot, and further announced that it would be donating $1,000 a month going forward, in the interest of supporting an open-source alternative to Unity.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Two years later, Emilio Coppola of the Godot Foundation stated that the amount of contributions "doubled" as a result of the shift.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] In 2025, the Godot Foundation released an initial beta of the Godot Asset Store, intended as a replacement to the extant asset library.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] In June 2026, it replaced the asset library as part of version 4.7.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] In April 2026, Marcus Chen of *Tech Insider* compared Godot and Unity in various aspects.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Chen noted that Godot's GDScript was similar to pseudocode and more accessible than Unity's main programming language C#, which Godot also supported in addition to C++ and Python.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] He also highlighted the free and open source nature of Godot also contrasted Unity's pay model, making the former relevant for developers with limited or zero budgets.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Conversely, video game console support and third-party tool support were noted as advantageous for Unity.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Additionally, due to its longer presence on the market, Unity was reported by Chen to feature more available assets in its asset store and a larger job market.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] An in-depth performance comparison between Unity and Godot was made in May 2026 by Studio Interrupt founder Thomas Grové, who created the same project across the two engines.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Grové concluded that Unity had a higher rendering performance, while Godot saw significant advantages in project loading and compiling speeds as well as having a file size of 164 megabytes, compared to Unity's 20 gigabytes.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot reached version 1.0 on 15 December 2014, marking the first stable release and the addition of lightmapping, navmesh support, and more shaders.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Version 1.1 was released on 21 May 2015, adding improved auto-completion in the code editor, a visual shader editor, a new API to the operating system for managing screens and windows, improved 2D physics and a rewritten 2D engine, better Blender Collada support, and a new dark theme.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot 2.0 was released on 23 February 2016, adding better scene instancing and inheritance, a new file system browser, multiple scene editing, and an enhanced debugger.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] This was followed by version 2.1 in August 2016, which introduced an asset database, profiler, and plugin API.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Version 3.0 was released on 29 January 2018, adding a new PBR renderer implemented in OpenGL ES 3.0, virtual reality compatibility, and C# support (via Mono) thanks to a $24,000 donation from Microsoft.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Version 3.0 also added the Bullet physics engine in addition to the engine's built-in 3D physics back end and was the first version of Godot to be included in Debian.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot 3.1 was released on 13 March 2019, with the most notable features being the addition of statically typed § GDScript, a script class system for GDScript, and an OpenGL ES 2.0 renderer.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot 3.2 was released on 29 January 2020, with the most notable features being massive documentation improvements, greatly improved C# support, and support for glTF 2.0 files.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The lead developer, Juan Linietsky, spent most of his time working on a separate Vulkan branch that would later be merged into master for 4.0, so work on 3.2 was mostly done by other contributors.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot 3.3 was released on 21 April 2021, with features such as ARM support on macOS, Android App Bundles support, MP3 support, Autodesk FBX support, WebXR support, and a web editor.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot 3.4 was released on 6 November 2021 after six months of development, implementing missing features or bug fixes that are critical for publishing 2D and 3D games with Godot 3 and making existing features more optimized and reliable.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot 3.5 was released on 5 August 2022 after nine months of development.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Just like Godot 3.4, it was focused on implementing missing features or bug fixes important for 2D and 3D video games made with Godot 3.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Features include physics interpolation in 3D, asynchronous shader compilation, and more.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot 3.x was placed on a much slower schedule upon the initial distribution of the 4.0 beta, and as such Godot 3.6 was released on 9 September 2024 after two years of development.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The new release added 2D physics interpolation and hierarchical culling, and 3D mesh merging, level of detail, tighter shadow culling, ORM materials, and more.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] It is a major update that overhauls the rendering system, adds support for Vulkan graphics API, improves GDScript performance and usability, enhances physics and animation systems, and introduces many other features and bug fixes.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The development of Godot 4 started in 2019 with a rewrite of the renderer to use Vulkan by Linietsky.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] In 2020, several contributors joined the development team and worked on various aspects of Godot 4, such as GDScript improvements, physics engine overhaul, animation system rewrite, editor usability enhancements and more.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The first alpha version of Godot 4 was released for testing by early adopters in January 2022.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] It included new features such as SDF-based global illumination, GPU-based particles, and dynamic soft shadows.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] In September 2022, Godot 4 reached beta stage.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] It also added support for WebXR, C# support for Android and iOS, and new audio features.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] On 1 March 2023, Godot 4 was officially released as a stable version after several beta builds and bug fixes.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] This was followed by Godot 4.1 later in 2023, which added experimental scene multithreading, editor enhancements, and C# improvements.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot 4.2 was released at 30 November 2023, implementing a rework of the animation tool and particle system, improvements to the import pipeline, and added support for FSR 2.2.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot 4.3 was released on 15 August 2024, and added GPU synchronization via acyclic graphs, render pipeline compositor effects, and improved 3D animation retargeting.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Godot 4.4 was released on 5 March 2025, and introduced integration with the Jolt physics engine.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] This was followed by Godot 4.5 in September 2025, and introduced several features such as stencil buffer support and a rework of the TileMapLayer Collision System that merges placed cell shapes into bigger collision shapes whenever possible.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Version 4.6 was released in January 2026, adding the ability to be built as a standalone library and a new default theme.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] In June 2026, version 4.7 was released, including high dynamic range support, area lights, and drawable textures.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Many games by OKAM Studio have been made using Godot, including *Dog Mendonça & Pizza Boy*, which uses the Escoria adventure game extension.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] Additionally, it has been used in West Virginia's high school curriculum, due to its ease of use for non-programmers and already-existing learning materials.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] *Battlefield 6* uses Godot for its user-generated content creation platform, "*Battlefield Portal*".
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] The engine has been used in commercial projects, including Sega's development of *Sonic Colors Ultimate*.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] In 2007, Linietsky co-founded the Godot Engine project together with Manzur, aiming to provide a free and open-source alternative to proprietary game engines.
[src:gdscript-deep/gdscript] He has served as the lead developer since the project's inception, managing the engine's architecture and development roadmap.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] In computing, a **script** is a relatively short and simple set of instructions that typically automate an otherwise manual process.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] The act of writing a script is called **scripting**.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] A **scripting language** or **script language** is a programming language that is used for scripting.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Originally, scripting was limited to automating shells in operating systems, and languages were relatively simple.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Today, scripting is more pervasive and some scripting languages include modern features that allow them to be used to develop application software also.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] A scripting language can be a general-purpose programming language or a domain-specific language for a given environment.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] When embedded in an application, it may be called an *extension language*.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] A scripting language is sometimes referred to as very high-level programming language if it operates at a high level of abstraction, or as a *control language*, especially for job control languages on mainframe computers.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] The term *scripting language* is sometimes used in a wider sense, to refer to dynamic high-level programming languages in general.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Some are strictly interpreted languages, while others use a form of compilation.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] In this context, the term *script* refers to a small program in such a language.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Typically, a script is contained in a single file, and no larger than a few thousand lines of code.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] The scope of scripting languages ranges from small to large, and from highly domain-specific language to general-purpose programming languages.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] A language may start as small and highly domain-specific and later develop into a portable and general-purpose language; conversely, a general-purpose language may later develop special domain-specific dialects.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Script is a subjective characterization that generally includes the following attributes.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] A script is usually not compiled, at least not its usual meaning.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Generally, they are interpreted directly from source code, or from bytecode, or run as native after just-in-time compilation.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] A script is generally relatively short and simple.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] As there is no limit on size or complexity, script is subjective.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] A few lines of code without branching is probably considered a script.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] A codebase of multiple files, that performs sophisticated user or hardware interface or complicated algorithms or multiprogramming is probably not considered a script.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] A script usually automates a task that would otherwise be performed by a person in a more manual way.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] A language that is primarily intended for scripting generally has limited capabilities compared to a general-purpose language.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] A scripting language may lack the functionality to write complex applications.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Typically, a script starts executing at the first line of code whereas an application typically starts at a special point in the code called the entry point.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] For example, Java is not script-like since an application starts at the function named `main` which need not be at the top of the code.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] The following code starts at `main`, then calls `printHelloWorld` which prints "Hello World".
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] In contrast, the following Python code prints "Hello World" without the `main` function or other syntax such as a class definition required by Java.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Scripts are often created or modified by the person executing them, but they are also often distributed, such as when large portions of games are written in a scripting language, notably the Google Chrome T-rex game.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Early mainframe computers (in the 1950s) were non-interactive, instead using batch processing.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] IBM's Job Control Language (JCL) is the archetype of languages used to control batch processing.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] The first interactive shells were developed in the 1960s to enable remote operation of the first time-sharing systems, and these used shell scripts, which controlled running computer programs within a computer program, the shell.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Calvin Mooers in his TRAC language is generally credited with inventing *command substitution*, the ability to embed commands in scripts that, when interpreted, insert a character string into the script.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Louis Pouzin wrote an early processor for command scripts called RUNCOM for CTSS around 1964.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Stuart Madnick at MIT wrote a scripting language for IBM's CP/CMS in 1966.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] He originally called this processor COMMAND, later named EXEC.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Multics included an offshoot of CTSS RUNCOM, also called RUNCOM.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] EXEC was eventually replaced by EXEC 2 and Rexx.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Languages such as Tcl and Lua were specifically designed as general-purpose scripting languages that could be embedded in any application.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Other languages such as Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) provided strong integration with the automation facilities of an underlying system.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Embedding of such general-purpose scripting languages instead of developing a new language for each application also had obvious benefits, relieving the application developer of the need to code a language translator from scratch and allowing the user to apply skills learned elsewhere.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Some software incorporates several different scripting languages.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Modern web browsers typically provide a language for writing extensions to the browser itself, and several standard embedded languages for controlling the browser, including JavaScript (a dialect of ECMAScript) or XUL.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Scripting languages can be categorized into several different types, with a considerable degree of overlap among the types.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Scripting is often contrasted with system programming, as in Ousterhout's dichotomy or "programming in the large and programming in the small".
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] In this view, scripting is glue code, connecting software components, and a language specialized for this purpose is a *glue language*.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Pipelines and shell scripting are archetypal examples of glue languages, and Perl was initially developed to fill this same role.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Web development can be considered a use of glue languages, interfacing between a database and web server.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] But if a substantial amount of logic is written in script, it is better characterized as simply another software component, not "glue".
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Macro languages exposed to operating system or application components can serve as glue languages.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] These include Visual Basic for Applications, WordBasic, LotusScript, CorelScript, Hummingbird Basic, QuickScript, Rexx, SaxBasic, and WinWrap Basic.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Other tools like AWK can also be considered glue languages, as can any language implemented by a Windows Script Host engine (VBScript, JScript and VBA by default in Windows and third-party engines including implementations of Rexx, Perl, Tcl, Python, XSLT, Ruby, Modern Pascal, Delphi, and C).
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] A majority of applications can access and use operating system components via the object models or its own functions.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Depending upon the OS version, WSH and the default script engines (VBScript and JScript) are available.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Programmable calculators can be programmed in glue languages in three ways.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] For example, the Texas Instruments TI-92, by factory default can be programmed with a command script language.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Inclusion of the scripting and glue language Lua in the TI-NSpire series of calculators could be seen as a successor to this.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] The primary on-board high-level programming languages of most graphing calculators (most often Basic variants, sometimes Lisp derivatives, and more uncommonly, C derivatives) in many cases can glue together calculator functions—such as graphs, lists, matrices, etc.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Third-party implementations of more comprehensive Basic version that may be closer to variants listed as glue languages in this article are available—and attempts to implement Perl, Rexx, or various operating system shells on the TI and HP graphing calculators are also mentioned.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] A number of text editors support macros written either using a macro language built into the editor, e.g., The SemWare Editor (TSE), vi improved (VIM), or using an external implementation, e.g., XEDIT, or both, e.g., KEDIT.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Sometimes text editors and edit macros are used under the covers to provide other applications, e.g., FILELIST and RDRLIST in CMS .
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Many of these languages' interpreters double as command-line interpreters such as the Unix shell or the MS-DOS `COMMAND.COM`.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Others, such as AppleScript offer the use of English-like commands to build scripts.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] With the advent of graphical user interfaces, a specialized kind of scripting language emerged for controlling a computer.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] These languages interact with the same graphic windows, menus, buttons, and so on, that a human user would.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] They do this by simulating the actions of a user.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] These languages are typically used to automate user actions.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Such languages are also called *macros* when control is through simulated key presses or mouse clicks, and tapping or pressing on a touch-activated screen.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] These languages could in principle be used to control any GUI application, but in practice their use is limited because they need support from the application and from the operating system.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] There are a few exceptions to this limit.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Some GUI scripting languages are based on recognizing graphical objects from their display screen pixels.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] These GUI scripting languages do not depend on support from the operating system or application.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] When the GUI provides the appropriate interfaces, as in the IBM Workplace Shell, a generic scripting language, e.g., Object REXX, can be used to write GUI scripts.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Likewise, many computer game systems use a custom scripting language to express the programmed actions of non-player characters and the game environment.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Languages of this sort are designed for a single application; while they may superficially resemble a specific general-purpose language (e.g., QuakeC, modeled after C), they have custom features that distinguish them.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Emacs Lisp, while a fully formed and capable dialect of Lisp, contains many special features that make it most useful for extending the editing functions of Emacs.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] An application-specific scripting language can be viewed as a domain-specific programming language specialized to one application.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] A number of languages have been designed for the purpose of replacing application-specific scripting languages by being embeddable in application programs.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] The application programmer (working in C or another systems language) includes "hooks" where the scripting language can control the application.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] These languages may be technically equivalent to an application-specific extension language but when an application embeds a "common" language, the user gets the advantage of being able to transfer skills from application to application.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] A more generic alternative is simply to provide a library (often a C library) that a general-purpose language can use to control the application, without modifying the language for the specific domain.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] JavaScript began as, and still is mostly, a language for scripting inside web browsers.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] However, the standardizing of the language as ECMAScript has made it popular as a general-purpose embeddable language.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] The Mozilla implementation SpiderMonkey is embedded in several environments such as the Yahoo Widgets Engine,and applications such as the Adobe products Flash (ActionScript) and Acrobat (for scripting PDF files).
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Tcl was created as an extension language but has come to be used more often as a general-purpose language in roles similar to Python, Perl, and Ruby.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] In contrast, Rexx was created as a job control language, but is widely used as an extension language and a general-purpose language.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Perl is a general-purpose language, but had the Oraperl (1990) dialect, consisting of a Perl 4 binary with Oracle Call Interface compiled in.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] This has however since been replaced by a library (Perl Module), DBD::Oracle.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Other complex and task-oriented applications may incorporate and expose an embedded programming language to allow their users more control and give them more functionality than can be available through a user interface, no matter how sophisticated.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] For example, Autodesk Maya 3D authoring tools embed the Maya Embedded Language, or Blender which uses Python to fill this role.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] Some other types of applications that need faster feature addition or tweak-and-run cycles (e.g. game engines) also use an embedded language.
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] During the development, this allows them to prototype features faster and tweak more freely, without the need for the user to have intimate knowledge of the inner workings of the application or to rebuild it after each tweak (which can take a significant amount of time).
[src:gdscript-deep/scripting-language] The scripting languages used for this purpose range from the more common and more famous Lua and Python to lesser-known ones such as AngelScript and Squirrel.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Most modern video games are audiovisual, with audio complement delivered through speakers or headphones, and sometimes also with other types of sensory feedback (e.g., haptic technology that provides tactile sensations).
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Some video games also allow microphone and webcam inputs for in-game chatting and livestreaming.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Video games are typically categorized according to their hardware platform, which traditionally includes arcade video games, console games, and computer games (which includes LAN games, online games, and browser games).
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] More recently, the video game industry has expanded onto mobile gaming through mobile devices (such as smartphones and tablet computers), virtual and augmented reality systems, and remote cloud gaming.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Video games are also classified into a wide range of genres based on their style of gameplay and target audience.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The first video game prototypes in the 1950s and 1960s were simple extensions of electronic games using video-like output from large, room-sized mainframe computers.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The first consumer video game was the arcade video game *Computer Space* in 1971, which took inspiration from the earlier 1962 computer game *Spacewar!*.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] In 1972 came the now-iconic video game *Pong* and the first home console, the Magnavox Odyssey.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The industry grew quickly during the "golden age" of arcade video games from the late 1970s to early 1980s but suffered from the crash of the North American video game market in 1983 due to loss of publishing control and saturation of the market.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Following the crash, the industry matured, was dominated by Japanese companies such as Nintendo, Sega, and Sony, and established practices and methods around the development and distribution of video games to prevent a similar crash in the future, many of which continue to be followed.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] In the 2000s, the core industry centered on "AAA" games, leaving little room for riskier experimental games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Coupled with the availability of the Internet and digital distribution, this gave room for independent video game development (or "indie games") to gain prominence into the 2010s.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Since then, the commercial importance of the video game industry has been increasing.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The emerging Asian markets and proliferation of smartphone games in particular are altering player demographics towards casual and cozy gaming, and increasing monetization by incorporating games as a service.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Today, video game development requires numerous skills, vision, teamwork, and liaisons between different parties, including developers, publishers, distributors, retailers, hardware manufacturers, and other marketers, to successfully bring a game to its consumers.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The video game market is also a major influence behind the electronics industry, where personal computer component, console, and peripheral sales, as well as consumer demands for better game performance, have been powerful driving factors for hardware design and innovation.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Early video games used interactive electronic devices with various display formats.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The earliest example dates to 1947—a "cathode-ray tube amusement device" was filed for a patent on 25 January 1947, by Thomas T.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Goldsmith Jr. and Estle Ray Mann, and issued on 14 December 1948, as U.S.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Inspired by radar display technology, it consisted of an analog device allowing a user to control the parabolic arc of a dot on the screen to simulate a missile being fired at targets, which were paper drawings fixed to the screen.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Other early examples include the Nimrod computer at the 1951 Festival of Britain; Christopher Strachey's *Checkers*, possibly the first game to display visuals on an electronic screen in 1952; *OXO*, a tic-tac-toe computer game by Alexander S.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Douglas for the EDSAC in 1952; *Tennis for Two*, an electronic interactive game engineered by William Higinbotham in 1958; and *Spacewar!*, written by Massachusetts Institute of Technology students Martin Graetz, Steve Russell, and Wayne Wiitanen's on a DEC PDP-1 computer in 1962.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] These inventions laid the foundation for modern video games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] In 1966, while working at Sanders Associates, Ralph H.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Baer devised a system to play a basic table tennis game on a television screen.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] With the company's approval, Baer created the prototype known as the "Brown Box".
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Sanders patented Baer's innovations and licensed them to Magnavox, which commercialized the technology as the first home video game console, the Magnavox Odyssey, released in 1972.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Separately, Nolan Bushnell and Ted Dabney, inspired by seeing *Spacewar!* running at Stanford University, devised a similar version running in a smaller coin-operated arcade cabinet using a less expensive computer.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] This was released as *Computer Space*, the first arcade video game, in 1971.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Bushnell and Dabney went on to form Atari, Inc., and with Allan Alcorn, created their second arcade game in 1972, the hit ping pong-style *Pong*, which was directly inspired by the table tennis game on the Odyssey.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Atari made a home version of *Pong*, which was released by Christmas 1975.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The success of the Odyssey and *Pong*, both as an arcade game and home machine, launched the video game industry.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Both Baer and Bushnell have been titled "Father of Video Games" for their contributions.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The term "video game" was developed to describe electronic games played on a video display rather than on a teletype printer, audio speaker, or similar device.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] This also distinguished from handheld electronic games such as *Merlin,* which commonly used LED lights for indicators not in combination for imaging purposes.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] "Computer game" may also be used as a descriptor, as all these types of games essentially require the use of a computer processor; in some cases, it is used interchangeably with "video game".
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Particularly in the United Kingdom and Western Europe, this is common due to the historic relevance of domestically produced microcomputers.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Other terms used include digital game, for example, by the Australian Bureau of Statistics.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The term "computer game" can also refer to PC games, which are played primarily on personal computers or other flexible hardware systems, to distinguish them from console games, arcade games, or mobile games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Other terms, such as "television game", "telegame", or "TV game", had been used in the 1970s and early 1980s, particularly for home gaming consoles that rely on connection to a television set.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] However, these terms were also used interchangeably with "video game" in the 1970s, primarily due to "video" and "television" being synonymous.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] In Japan, where consoles like the Odyssey were first imported and then made within the country by the large television manufacturers such as Toshiba and Sharp Corporation, such games are known as "TV games", "TV geemu", or "terebi geemu".
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The term "TV game" is still commonly used into the 21st century.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] "Electronic game" may also be used to refer to video games, but this also incorporates devices like early handheld electronic games that lack any video output.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The first appearance of the term "video game" emerged around 1973.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The Oxford English Dictionary cited a 10 November 1973 *BusinessWeek* article as the first printed use of the term.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Though Bushnell believed the term came from a vending magazine review of *Computer Space* in 1971, a review of the major vending magazines *Vending Times* and *Cashbox* showed that the term may have come even earlier, appearing first in a letter dated July 10, 1972.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] In the letter, Bushnell uses the term "video game" twice.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Per video game historian Keith Smith, the sudden appearance suggested that the term had been proposed and readily adopted by those in the field.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Around March 1973, Ed Adlum, who ran *Cashbox*'s coin-operated section until 1972 and then later founded *RePlay Magazine*, covering the coin-op amusement field, in 1975, used the term in an article in March 1973.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] In a September 1982 issue of *RePlay*, Adlum is credited with first naming these games as "video games": "RePlay's Eddie Adlum worked at 'Cash Box' when 'TV games' first came out.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The personalities in those days were Bushnell, his sales manager Pat Karns, and a handful of other 'TV game' manufacturers like Henry Leyser and the McEwan brothers.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] With the arrival of video games in arcades during the early 1970s, there was initially some confusion in the arcade industry over what term should be used to describe the new games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] While many games readily fall into a clear, well-understood definition of video games, new genres and innovations in game development have raised the question of what are the essential factors of a video game that separate the medium from other forms of entertainment.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The introduction of interactive films in the 1980s with games like *Dragon's Lair*, featured games with full motion video played off a form of media but only limited user interaction.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] This had required a means to distinguish these games from more traditional board games that happen to also use external media, such as the *Clue VCR Mystery Game* which required players to watch VCR clips between turns.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] To distinguish between these two, video games are considered to require some interactivity that affects the visual display.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Most video games tend to feature some type of victory or winning conditions, such as a scoring mechanism or a final boss fight.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] These are still commonly justified as video games as they provide a game world that the player can interact with by some means.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The lack of any industry definition for a video game by 2021 was an issue during the case *Epic Games v.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Apple* which dealt with video games offered on Apple's iOS App Store.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Among concerns raised were games like *Fortnite Creative* and *Roblox* which created metaverses of interactive experiences, and whether the larger game and the individual experiences themselves were games or not in relation to fees that Apple charged for the App Store.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Rogers still concluded that what is a video game "appears highly eclectic and diverse".
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The gameplay experience varies radically between video games, but many common elements exist.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Most games will launch into a title screen and give the player a chance to review options such as the number of players before starting a game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Most games are divided into levels which the player must work the avatar through, scoring points, collecting power-ups to boost the avatar's innate attributes, all while either using special attacks to defeat enemies or moves to avoid them.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] This information is relayed to the player through a type of on-screen user interface such as a heads-up display atop the rendering of the game itself.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Taking damage will deplete their avatar's health, and if that falls to zero or if the avatar otherwise falls into an impossible-to-escape location, the player will lose one of their lives.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Should they lose all their lives without gaining an extra life or "1-UP", then the player will reach the "game over" screen.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Many levels as well as the game's finale end with a type of boss character the player must defeat to continue on.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] In some games, intermediate points between levels will offer save points where the player can create a saved game on storage media to restart the game should they lose all their lives or need to stop the game and restart at a later time.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] These also may be in the form of a passage that can be written down and reentered at the title screen.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Product flaws include software bugs which can manifest as glitches which may be exploited by the player; this is often the foundation of speedrunning a video game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] These bugs, along with cheat codes, Easter eggs, and other hidden secrets that were intentionally added to the game can also be exploited.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] On some consoles, cheat cartridges allow players to execute these cheat codes, and user-developed trainers allow similar bypassing for computer software games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Both of which might make the game easier, give the player additional power-ups, or change the appearance of the game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] To distinguish from electronic games, a video game is generally considered to require a platform, the hardware which contains computing elements, to process player interaction from some type of input device and displays the results to a video output display.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Video games require a platform, a specific combination of electronic components or computer hardware and associated software, to operate.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] These platforms may include multiple brandsheld by platform holders, such as Nintendo or Sony, seeking to gain larger market shares.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Games are typically designed to be played on one or a limited number of platforms, and exclusivity to a platform or brand is used by platform holders as a competitive edge in the video game market.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] However, games may be developed for alternative platforms than intended, which are described as ports or conversions.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] These also may be remasters - where most of the original game's source code is reused and art assets, models, and game levels are updated for modern systems – and remakes, where in addition to asset improvements, significant reworking of the original game and possibly from scratch is performed.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The list below is not exhaustive and excludes other electronic devices capable of playing video games such as PDAs and graphing calculators.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Personal computers are not dedicated game platforms, so there may be differences running the same game on different hardware.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] (in which a person plays a video game with people who are in a different household) and others.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] is a PC or laptop intended specifically for gaming, typically using high-performance, high-cost components.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] and other similarly shared systems, with users logging in remotely to use the computer.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] A console game is played on a home console, a specialized electronic device that connects to a common television set or composite video monitor.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Home consoles are specifically designed to play games using a dedicated hardware environment, giving developers a concrete hardware target for development and assurances of what features will be available, simplifying development compared to PC game development.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Usually consoles only run games developed for it, or games from other platform made by the same company, but never games developed by its direct competitor, even if the same game is available on different platforms.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] It often comes with a specific game controller.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Major console platforms include Xbox, PlayStation and Nintendo.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] is a small, self-contained electronic device that is portable and can be held in a user's hands.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Like consoles, handhelds are dedicated platforms, and share almost the same characteristics.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Handheld hardware usually is less powerful than PC or console hardware.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Some handheld games from the late 1970s and early 1980s could only play one game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] In the 1990s and 2000s, a number of handheld games used cartridges, which enabled them to be used to play many different games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The handheld console has waned in the 2010s as mobile device gaming has become a more dominant factor.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Arcade games often have brightly painted logos and images relating to the theme of the game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] While most arcade games are housed in a vertical cabinet, which the user typically stands in front of to play, some arcade games use a tabletop approach, in which the display screen is housed in a table-style cabinet with a see-through table top.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] With table-top games, the users typically sit to play.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] In the 1990s and 2000s, some arcade games offered players a choice of multiple games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] In the 1980s, video arcades were businesses in which game players could use a number of arcade video games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] In the 2010s, there are far fewer video arcades, but some movie theaters and family entertainment centers still have them.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] requires a minimal hardware device, such as a basic computer, console, laptop, mobile phone or even a dedicated hardware device connected to a display with good Internet connectivity that connects to hardware systems by the cloud gaming provider.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] between player input and output on their display device.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] to immerse a player within virtual environment that responds to their head movements.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Some VR systems include control units for the player's hands as to provide a direct way to interact with the virtual world.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] VR systems generally require a separate computer, console, or other processing device that couples with the head-mounted unit.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] on a modern system, simulating the hardware of the original and allows old games to be played.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] While emulators themselves have been found to be legal in United States case law, the act of obtaining the game software that one does not already own may violate copyrights.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] is similar in nature to emulation in that older games can be played on newer platforms, but typically directly though hardware and built-in software within the platform.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Early arcade games, home consoles, and handheld games were dedicated hardware units with the game's logic built into the electronic componentry of the hardware.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Since then, most video game platforms are considered programmable, having means to read and play multiple games distributed on different types of media or formats.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Physical formats include ROM cartridges, magnetic storage including magnetic-tape data storage and floppy discs, optical media formats including CD-ROM and DVDs, and flash memory cards.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Furthermore digital distribution over the Internet or other communication methods as well as cloud gaming alleviate the need for any physical media.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] In some cases, the media serves as the direct read-only memory for the game, or it may be the form of installation media that is used to write the main assets to the player's platform's local storage for faster loading periods and later updates.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Games can be extended with new content and software patches through either expansion packs which are typically available as physical media, or as downloadable content nominally available via digital distribution.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] These can be offered freely or can be used to monetize a game following its initial release.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Several games offer players the ability to create user-generated content to share with others to play.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Other games, mostly those on personal computers, can be extended with user-created modifications or mods that alter or add onto the game; these often are unofficial and were developed by players from reverse engineering of the game, but other games provide official support for modding the game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Video game can use several types of input devices to translate human actions to a game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Most common are the use of game controllers like gamepads and joysticks for most consoles, and as accessories for personal computer systems along keyboard and mouse controls.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Common controls on the most recent controllers include face buttons, shoulder triggers, analog sticks, and directional pads ("d-pads").
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Consoles typically include standard controllers which are shipped or bundled with the console itself, while peripheral controllers are available as a separate purchase from the console manufacturer or third-party vendors.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Similar control sets are built into handheld consoles and onto arcade cabinets.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Newer technology improvements have incorporated additional technology into the controller or the game platform, such as touchscreens and motion detection sensors that give more options for how the player interacts with the game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Specialized controllers may be used for certain genres of games, including racing wheels, light guns and dance pads.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Digital cameras and motion detection can capture movements of the player as input into the game, which can, in some cases, effectively eliminate the control, and on other systems such as virtual reality, are used to enhance immersion into the game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] By definition, all video games are intended to output graphics to an external video display, such as cathode ray tube televisions, newer liquid-crystal display (LCD) televisions and built-in screens, projectors or computer monitors, depending on the type of platform the game is played on.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Features such as color depth, refresh rate, frame rate, and screen resolution are a combination of the limitations of the game platform and display device and the program efficiency of the game itself.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The game's output can range from fixed displays using LED or LCD elements, text-based games, two-dimensional and three-dimensional graphics, and augmented reality displays.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The game's graphics are often accompanied by sound produced by internal speakers on the game platform or external speakers attached to the platform, as directed by the game's programming.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] This often will include sound effects tied to the player's actions to provide audio feedback, as well as background music for the game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Some platforms support additional feedback mechanics to the player that a game can take advantage of.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] This is most commonly haptic technology built into the game controller, such as causing the controller to shake in the player's hands to simulate a shaking earthquake occurring in game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Video games are frequently classified by a number of factors related to how one plays them.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] A video game, like most other forms of media, may be categorized into genres.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] However, unlike film or television which use visual or narrative elements, video games are generally categorized into genres based on their gameplay interaction, since this is the primary means which one interacts with a video game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The narrative setting does not impact gameplay; a shooter game is still a shooter game, regardless of whether it takes place in a fantasy world or in outer space.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] An exception is the horror game genre, used for games that are based on narrative elements of horror fiction, the supernatural, and psychological horror.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The names may shift over time as players, developers and the media come up with new terms; for example, first-person shooters were originally called "Doom clones" based on the 1993 game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] A hierarchy of game genres exist, with top-level genres like "shooter game" and "action game" that broadly capture the game's main gameplay style, and several subgenres of specific implementation, such as within the shooter game first-person shooter and third-person shooter.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Some cross-genre types also exist that fall until multiple top-level genres such as action-adventure game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] A video game's mode describes how many players can use the game at the same type.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] This is primarily distinguished by single-player video games and multiplayer video games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Within the latter category, multiplayer games can be played in a variety of ways, including locally at the same device, on separate devices connected through a local network such as LAN parties, or online via separate Internet connections.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Most multiplayer games are based on competitive gameplay, but many offer cooperative and team-based options as well as asymmetric gameplay.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Online games use server structures that can also enable massively multiplayer online games (MMOs) to support hundreds of players at the same time.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] A small number of video games are zero-player games, in which the player has very limited interaction with the game itself.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] These are most commonly simulation games where the player may establish a starting state and then let the game proceed on its own, watching the results as a passive observer, such as with many computerized simulations of Conway's Game of Life.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Most video games are intended for entertainment purposes.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Core or hard-core games refer to the typical perception of video games, developed for entertainment purposes.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] These games typically require a fair amount of time to learn and master, in contrast to casual games, and thus are most appealing to gamers rather than a broader audience.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Most of the AAA video game industry is based around the delivery of core games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] They frequently support the ability to jump in and out of play on demand, such as during commuting or lunch breaks.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] mechanics, where players can enlist the help of friends on their social media networks for extra turns or moves each day.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] has been used in homes and classrooms to help teach children and students, and video games have been similarly adapted for these reasons, all designed to provide a form of interactivity and entertainment tied to game design elements.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] There are a variety of differences in their designs and how they educate the user.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] that are geared towards problem solving through motivation and positive reinforcement while downplaying the entertainment value.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] are those where the entertainment factor may be augmented, overshadowed, or even eliminated by other purposes for the game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Although video games have been considered an art form on their own, games may be developed to try to purposely communicate a story or message, using the medium as a work of art.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] are designed to generate emotion and empathy from the player by challenging societal norms and offering critique through the interactivity of the video game medium.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] They may not have any type of win condition and are designed to let the player explore through the game world and scenarios.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] in nature, designed based on personal experiences or stories through a single developer or small team.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Video games can be subject to national and international content rating requirements.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Like with film content ratings, video game ratings typing identify the target age group that the national or regional ratings board believes is appropriate for the player, ranging from all-ages, to a teenager-or-older, to mature, to the infrequent adult-only games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Most content review is based on the level of violence, both in the type of violence and how graphic it may be represented, and sexual content, but other themes such as drug and alcohol use and gambling that can influence children may also be identified.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] A primary identifier based on a minimum age is used by nearly all systems, along with additional descriptors to identify specific content that players and parents should be aware of.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The regulations vary from country to country but generally are voluntary systems upheld by vendor practices, with penalty and fines issued by the ratings body on the video game publisher for misuse of the ratings.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Certain nations have even more restrictive rules related to political or ideological content.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Within Germany, until 2018, the Unterhaltungssoftware Selbstkontrolle (*Entertainment Software Self-Regulation*) would refuse to classify, and thus allow sale, of any game depicting Nazi imagery, and thus often requiring developers to replace such imagery with fictional ones.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] This ruling was relaxed in 2018 to allow for such imagery for "social adequacy" purposes that applied to other works of art.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] China's video game segment is mostly isolated from the rest of the world due to the government's censorship, and all games published there must adhere to strict government review, disallowing content such as smearing the image of the Chinese Communist Party.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Foreign games published in China often require modification by developers and publishers to meet these requirements.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Video game development and authorship, much like any other form of entertainment, is frequently a cross-disciplinary field.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Video game developers, as employees within this industry are commonly referred to, primarily include programmers and graphic designers.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Over the years, this has expanded to include almost every type of skill that one might see prevalent in the creation of any movie or television program, including sound designers, musicians, and other technicians; as well as skills that are specific to video games, such as the game designer.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] In the early days of the industry, it was more common for a single person to manage all of the roles needed to create a video game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] As platforms have become more complex and powerful in the type of material they can present, larger teams have been needed to generate all of the art, programming, cinematography, and more.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Video games are programmed like any other piece of computer software.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Prior to the mid-1970s, arcade and home consoles were programmed by assembling discrete electro-mechanical components on circuit boards, which limited games to relatively simple logic.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] By 1975, low-cost microprocessors were available at volume to be used for video game hardware, which allowed game developers to program more detailed games, widening the scope of what was possible.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Ongoing improvements in computer hardware technology have expanded what has become possible to create in video games, coupled with convergence of common hardware between console, computer, and arcade platforms to simplify the development process.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Today, game developers have a number of commercial and open source tools available for use to make games, often which are across multiple platforms to support portability, or may still opt to create their own for more specialized features and direct control of the game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Today, many games are built around a game engine that handles the bulk of the game's logic, gameplay, and rendering.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] These engines can be augmented with specialized engines for specific features, such as a physics engine that simulates the physics of objects in real-time.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] A variety of middleware exists to help developers access other features, such as playback of videos within games, network-oriented code for games that communicate via online services, matchmaking for online games, and similar features.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] These features can be used from a developer's programming language of choice, or they may opt to also use game development kits that minimize the amount of direct programming they have to do but can also limit the amount of customization they can add into a game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Like all software, video games usually undergo quality testing before release to assure there are no bugs or glitches in the product, though frequently developers will release patches and updates.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] With the growth of the size of development teams in the industry, the problem of cost has increased.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Development studios need the best talent, while publishers reduce costs to maintain profitability on their investment.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Typically, a video game console development team ranges from 5 to 50 people, and some exceed 100.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] In May 2009, *Assassin's Creed II* was reported to have a development staff of 450.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The growth of team size combined with greater pressure to get completed projects into the market to begin recouping production costs has led to a greater occurrence of missed deadlines, rushed games, and the release of unfinished products.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] While amateur and hobbyist game programming had existed since the late 1970s with the introduction of home computers, a newer trend since the mid-2000s is indie game development.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Indie games are made by small teams outside any direct publisher control, their games being smaller in scope than those from the larger "AAA" game studios, and are often experiments in gameplay and art style.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Indie game development is aided by the larger availability of digital distribution, including the newer mobile gaming market, and readily-available and low-cost development tools for these platforms.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Although departments of computer science have been studying technical aspects of video games for years, theories that examine games as an artistic medium are a relatively recent development.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The two most visible schools in this field are ludology and narratology.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Narrativists approach video games in the context of what Janet Murray calls "Cyberdrama".
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] That is to say, their major concern is with video games as a storytelling medium, one that arises out of interactive fiction.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Murray puts video games in the context of the Holodeck, a fictional piece of technology from *Star Trek*, arguing for the video game as a medium in which the player is allowed to become another person, and to act out in another world.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] This image of video games received early widespread popular support, and forms the basis of films such as *Tron*, *eXistenZ* and *The Last Starfighter*.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Ludologists break sharply and radically from this idea.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] They argue that a video game is first and foremost a game, which must be understood in terms of its rules, interface, and the concept of play that it deploys.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Espen Aarseth argues that, although games certainly have plots, characters, and aspects of traditional narratives, these aspects are incidental to gameplay.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] While many games rely on emergent principles, video games commonly present simulated story worlds where emergent behavior occurs within the context of the game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The term "emergent narrative" has been used to describe how, in a simulated environment, storyline can be created simply by "what happens to the player." However, emergent behavior is not limited to sophisticated games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] In general, any place where event-driven instructions occur for AI in a game, emergent behavior will exist.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] For instance, take a racing game in which cars are programmed to avoid crashing, and they encounter an obstacle in the track: the cars might then maneuver to avoid the obstacle causing the cars behind them to slow or maneuver to accommodate the cars in front of them and the obstacle.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The programmer never wrote code to specifically create a traffic jam, yet one now exists in the game.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Most commonly, video games are protected by copyright, though both patents and trademarks have been used as well.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Though local copyright regulations vary to the degree of protection, video games qualify as copyrighted visual-audio works, and enjoy cross-country protection under the Berne Convention.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] This typically only applies to the underlying code, as well as to the artistic aspects of the game such as its writing, art assets, and music.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Because gameplay is normally ineligible for copyright, gameplay ideas in popular games are often replicated and built upon in other games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] At times, this repurposing of gameplay can be seen as beneficial and a fundamental part of how the industry has grown by building on the ideas of others.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] For example *Doom* (1993) and *Grand Theft Auto III* (2001) introduced gameplay that created popular new game genres, the first-person shooter and the *Grand Theft Auto* clone, respectively, in the few years after their release.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] However, at times and more frequently at the onset of the industry, developers would intentionally create video game clones of successful games and game hardware with few changes, which led to the flooded arcade and dedicated home console market around 1978.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] Cloning is also a major issue with countries that do not have strong intellectual property protection laws, such as within China.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The lax oversight by China's government and the difficulty for foreign companies to take Chinese entities to court had enabled China to support a large grey market of cloned hardware and software systems.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p01] The industry remains challenged to distinguish between creating new games based on refinements of past successful games to create a new type of gameplay, and intentionally creating a clone of a game that may simply swap out art assets.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] The early history of the video game industry, following the first game hardware releases and through 1983, had little structure.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Video games quickly took off during the golden age of arcade video games from the late 1970s to early 1980s, but the newfound industry was mainly composed of game developers with little business experience.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] This led to numerous companies forming simply to create clones of popular games to try to capitalize on the market.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Due to loss of publishing control and oversaturation of the market, the North American home video game market crashed in 1983, dropping from revenues of around $3 billion in 1983 to $100 million by 1985.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Many of the North American companies created in the prior years closed down.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Japan's growing game industry was briefly shocked by this crash but had sufficient longevity to withstand the short-term effects, and Nintendo helped to revitalize the industry with the release of the Nintendo Entertainment System in North America in 1985.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Along with it, Nintendo established a number of core industrial practices to prevent unlicensed game development and control game distribution on their platform, methods that continue to be used by console manufacturers today.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] The industry remained more conservative following the 1983 crash, forming around the concept of publisher-developer dichotomies, and by the 2000s, leading to the industry centralizing around low-risk, triple-A games and studios with large development budgets of at least $10 million or more.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Video games have a large network effect that draw on many different sectors that tie into the larger video game industry.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] The industry itself grew out from both the United States and Japan in the 1970s and 1980s before having a larger worldwide contribution.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Today, the video game industry is predominantly led by major companies in North America (primarily the United States and Canada), Europe, and southeast Asia including Japan, South Korea, and China.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Hardware production remains an area dominated by Asian companies either directly involved in hardware design or part of the production process, but digital distribution and indie game development of the late 2000s has allowed game developers to flourish nearly anywhere and diversify the field.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] According to the market research firm Newzoo, the global video game industry drew estimated revenues of over $159 billion in 2020.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Mobile games accounted for the bulk of this, with a 48% share of the market, followed by console games at 28% and personal computer games at 23%.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Sales of different types of games vary widely between countries due to local preferences.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Japanese consumers tend to purchase much more handheld games than console games and especially PC games, with a strong preference for games catering to local tastes.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Another key difference is that, though having declined in the West, arcade games remain an important sector of the Japanese gaming industry.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] In South Korea, computer games are generally preferred over console games, especially MMORPG games and real-time strategy games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Computer games are also popular in China.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Video game culture is a worldwide new media subculture formed around video games and game playing.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] As computer and video games have increased in popularity over time, they have had a significant influence on popular culture.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Video game culture has also evolved over time hand in hand with internet culture as well as the increasing popularity of mobile games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Many people who play video games identify as gamers, which can mean anything from someone who enjoys games to someone who is passionate about it.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] As video games become more social with multiplayer and online capability, gamers find themselves in growing social networks.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Gaming can both be entertainment as well as competition, as a new trend known as electronic sports is becoming more widely accepted.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] In the 2010s, video games and discussions of video game trends and topics can be seen in social media, politics, television, film and music.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] The COVID-19 pandemic during 2020–2021 gave further visibility to video games as a pastime to enjoy with friends and family online as a means of social distancing.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Since the mid-2000s there has been debate whether video games qualify as art, primarily as the form's interactivity interfered with the artistic intent of the work and that they are designed for commercial appeal.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] A significant debate on the matter came after film critic Roger Ebert published an essay "Video Games can never be art", which challenged the industry to prove him and other critics wrong.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] The view that video games were an art form was cemented in 2011 when the U.S.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Supreme Court ruled in the landmark case *Brown v.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Entertainment Merchants Association* that video games were a protected form of speech with artistic merit.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Video games will inspire sequels and other video games within the same franchise, but also have influenced works outside of the video game medium.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Numerous television shows (both animated and live-action), films, comics and novels have been created based on existing video game franchises.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Because video games are an interactive medium there has been trouble in converting them to these passive forms of media, and typically such works have been critically panned or treated as children's media.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] That said, some early video game-based films have been highly successful at the box office, such as 1995's *Mortal Kombat* and 2001's *Lara Croft: Tomb Raider*.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] More recently since the 2000s, there has also become a larger appreciation of video game music, which ranges from chiptunes composed for limited sound-output devices on early computers and consoles, to fully-scored compositions for most modern games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Such music has frequently served as a platform for covers and remixes, and concerts featuring video game soundtracks performed by bands or orchestras, such as *Video Games Live*, have also become popular.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Video games also frequently incorporate licensed music, particularly in the area of rhythm games, furthering the depth of which video games and music can work together.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Further, video games can serve as a virtual environment under full control of a producer to create new works.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] With the capability to render 3D actors and settings in real-time, a new type of work machinima (short for "machine cinema") grew out from using video game engines to craft narratives.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] As video game engines gain higher fidelity, they have also become part of the tools used in more traditional filmmaking.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Unreal Engine has been used as a backbone by Industrial Light & Magic for their StageCraft technology for shows like *The Mandalorian*.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Separately, video games are also frequently used as part of the promotion and marketing for other media, such as for films, anime, and comics.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] However, these licensed games in the 1990s and 2000s often had a reputation for poor quality, developed without any input from the intellectual property rights owners, and several of them are considered among lists of games with notably negative reception, such as *Superman 64*.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] More recently, with these licensed games being developed by triple-A studios or through studios directly connected to the licensed property owner, there has been a significant improvement in the quality of these games, with an early trendsetting example of *Batman: Arkham Asylum*.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Besides their entertainment value, appropriately-designed video games have been seen to provide value in education across several ages and comprehension levels.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Learning principles found in video games have been identified as possible techniques with which to reform the U.S. education system.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] It has been noticed that gamers adopt an attitude while playing that is of such high concentration, they do not realize they are learning, and that if the same attitude could be adopted at school, education would enjoy significant benefits.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Students are found to be "learning by doing" while playing video games while fostering creative thinking.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Video games are also believed to be beneficial to the mind and body.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] It has been shown that action video game players have better hand–eye coordination and visuo-motor skills, such as their resistance to distraction, their sensitivity to information in the peripheral vision and their ability to count briefly presented objects, than nonplayers.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Researchers found that such enhanced abilities could be acquired by training with action games, involving challenges that switch attention between different locations, but not with games requiring concentration on single objects.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] A 2018 systematic review found evidence that video gaming training had positive effects on cognitive and emotional skills in the adult population, especially with young adults.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] A 2019 systematic review also added support for the claim that video games are beneficial to the brain, although the beneficial effects of video gaming on the brain differed by video games types.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Organisers of video gaming events, such as the organisers of the *D-Lux* video game festival in Dumfries, Scotland, have emphasised the positive aspects video games can have on mental health.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Organisers, mental health workers and mental health nurses at the event emphasised the relationships and friendships that can be built around video games and how playing games can help people learn about others as a precursor to discussing the person's mental health.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] A study in 2020 from Oxford University also suggested that playing video games can be a benefit to a person's mental health.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] The report of 3,274 gamers, all over the age of 18, focused on the games Animal Crossing: New Horizons and Plants vs Zombies: Battle for Neighborville and used actual play-time data.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] The report found that those that played more games tended to report greater "wellbeing".
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Also in 2020, computer science professor Regan Mandryk of the University of Saskatchewan said her research also showed that video games can have health benefits such as reducing stress and improving mental health.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] The university's research studied all age groups – "from pre-literate children through to older adults living in long term care homes" – with a main focus on 18 to 55-year-olds.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] A study of gamers attitudes towards gaming which was reported about in 2018 found that millennials use video games as a key strategy for coping with stress.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] In the study of 1,000 gamers, 55% said that it "helps them to unwind and relieve stress ... and half said they see the value in gaming as a method of escapism to help them deal with daily work pressures".
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Video games have caused controversy since the 1970s.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Medical experts and mental health professionals have also raised concerned that video games may be addictive, and the World Health Organization has included "gaming disorder" in the 11th revision of its International Statistical Classification of Diseases.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Even with case law establishing that video games qualify as a protected art form, there has been pressure on the video game industry to keep their products in check to avoid over-excessive violence particularly for games aimed at younger children.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] The industry as a whole has also dealt with issues related to gender, racial, and LGBTQ+ discrimination and mischaracterization of these minority groups in video games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] A further issue in the industry is related to working conditions, as development studios and publishers frequently use "crunch time", required extended working hours, in the weeks and months ahead of a game's release to assure on-time delivery.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Players of video games often maintain collections of games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] More recently there has been interest in retro gaming, focusing on games from the first decades.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Games in retail packaging in good shape have become collector's items for the early days of the industry, with some rare publications having gone for over US$100,000 as of 2020.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Separately, there is also concern about the preservation of video games, as both game media and the hardware to play them degrade over time.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Further, many of the game developers and publishers from the first decades no longer exist, so records of their games have disappeared.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Archivists and preservations have worked within the scope of copyright law to save these games as part of the cultural history of the industry.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] There are many video game museums around the world, including the National Videogame Museum in Frisco, Texas, which serves as the largest museum wholly dedicated to the display and preservation of the industry's most important artifacts.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] Europe hosts video game museums such as the Computer Games Museum in Berlin and the Museum of Soviet Arcade Machines in Moscow and Saint-Petersburg.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] The Museum of Art and Digital Entertainment in Oakland, California is a dedicated video game museum focusing on playable exhibits of console and computer games.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] The Video Game Museum of Rome is also dedicated to preserving video games and their history.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] The Smithsonian Institution in Washington, DC has three video games on permanent display: *Pac-Man*, *Dragon's Lair*, and *Pong*.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] The Museum of Modern Art has added a total of 20 video games and one video game console to its permanent Architecture and Design Collection since 2012.
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] In 2012, the Smithsonian American Art Museum ran an exhibition on "The Art of Video Games".
[src:gdscript-deep/video-game-p02] However, the reviews of the exhibit were mixed, including questioning whether video games belong in an art museum.
